After two factors had been extracted from each data set, the loadings observed for each item served as coordinates to locate the sentence in a circular space and to obtain its angular position and vector length2 (Wiggins & Broughton, 1991). Low vector lengths (VL < .30) were observed for four items in both data sets, and these were deleted; factor analysis was then conducted on the remaining 53 sentences. Table 2 shows how the items were circularly ordered around the two factors, for both self- and peer reports. We then used the following tests: Rao’s G test to verify whether the items were arranged uniformly around the circumference (Upton & Fingleton, 1989); Fisher’s variation coefficient to verify another property of a circumplex structure, that is, constant radius (Acton & Revelle, 2002; Fisher, 1997); Fisher’s A° to have a quantitative index of agreement for locations of like variables along the two circumplexes (Fisher, 1983); and Fisher’s χ2 to test the hypothesis that the agreement level between the two empirical circular arrays could have arisen by chance.3 G values were 305.8 (z = 1.697) and 274.8 (z = 0.408), respectively, for self- and peer ratings, indicating thereby that the empirical item arrays did not deviate from uniformity for the two data sets. Fisher’s variation coefficient values were .30 for self-ratings and .21 for peer ratings and indicated that the item distance from the center of the circular space was not constant. Mean angular separation (
θ ¯
) between corresponding item placements along the two circumplexes was equal to 24°, with a Fisher’s A° value of .87, indicating that the two circular arrays reached a substantive agreement degree, equal to 87% of the possible agreement. Moreover, the yielded Fisher’s χ2 value of 202.8 (df = 106, p < .05) showed that the angular positions of the 53 sentences along the two circumplexes were not generated by independent processes. Last, Table 2 shows that the item continua replicated the expected variable sequence, from LM- to JK-related sentences, indicating a substantial correspondence between the IPC model and the circular structure of children’s own interpersonal behavior ratings thereby. Yet strict psychometric criteria applied to evaluate this correspondence showed that 68% of the sentences were clustered within the expected IPC octant for peer ratings, but only 53% did so for self-ratings.

Table 4 presents the estimated communalities and angular positions of the IBQ-C scales (unequal-spacing/unequal-radius model). The empirical structures for self- and parents’ ratings were slightly rotated in an effort to better match the expected circular array. In fact, although CIRCUM requires indication of a reference variable, which is fixed at 0° (i.e., the LM octant), rotating the solutions does not influence the ordering of variables on the circle or the distances between variables on the circle and, therefore, has no impact on the model fit. Polar angles showed that each IBQ-C octant scale was located within its 45° theoretical arc, for each data set. Mean angular departures from target angles (
θ ¯
) ranged from 6.7° to 10.0°, with Fisher’s A° values ranging from .94 to .96 and demonstrating small misalignment levels (3.7% to 5.6% of the possible disagreement range). Fisher’s χ2 values were statistically significant, and they allowed the rejection of the null hypothesis of independence of the empirical circumplex structure from the expected circular array. Communalities (Table 4) were generally higher than .70, and coefficients of radius variations ranged from .058 (parents’ ratings) to .097 (peer ratings), indicating a constant radius for the IBQ-C circumplexes thereby.

